<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Niger </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Disputes Rebel Casualty Figures </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Disputes Rebel Casualty Figures </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB1905193094 Paris AFP in English 1917 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1905193094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Niamey, May 19 (AFP) -- Fifteen Tuareg rebels were 
killed and five government troops wounded when an Army patrol 
clashed with rebels trying to steal an official vehicle, 
Interior Minister Ousmane Oumarou told AFP Thursday [19 May]. 
  Five rebels were detained after the incident, which happened 
Monday between Assode and Timia, in the Iferouane region. 
  Troops seized a four-wheel drive vehicle, weapons, 
ammunition 
and various documents of the Front for the Liberation of the Air 
and Azawagh (FLAA), one of four Tuareg rebel movements in Niger. 
  The clash came after the government and the rebels last week 
said they would seek a negotiated end to the three-year conflict 
which has claimed more than 100 lives. 
  Officials from mediating countries -- Algeria, Burkina Faso 
and France -- met with delegates from the two sides last week 
and said the government and the rebels agreed in principle to a 
meeting soon. 
  Both sides last met in Ouagadougou in February. 

</TEXT>

