<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Nigeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Union Group Urges Participation in Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Union Group Urges Participation in Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB1905223594 Lagos NTA Television Network in English 2000 
GMT 19 May 994 </F>

<F P=103> AB1905223594 </F>
<F P=104>  Lagos NTA Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A group which includes a number of trade unionists 
has asked Nigerians not to do anything that would disrupt the 
Constitutional Conference election, scheduled for Monday [23 
May]. In a two-page statement, the group, which includes: 
Comrades Yomi Olusanya, Adetola Oseni, Chief Dayo Abata, Mrs. 
M.I. Akpankpa, Dr. David Ogunsede, and Chief Tayo Soyode, said 
it would be strategically unwise and politically suicidal for 
any ethnic group to boycott the proposed national constitutional 
conference. 
  The group recalled the experience of the nation in calling 
for a similar boycott order, by those it described as 
progressives in the 1964 federal elections, and declared that it 
would be wiser to use the constitutional conference platform to 
build a genuine national consensus for a fresh re-examination of 
the aborted democratic march, than to boycott it. According to 
the group, a boycott of the conference will turn the gathering 
into a conspiracy theater, and will not be in the long-term 
interest of any ethnic group. 

</TEXT>

