<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Togo </F>
<H3> <TI>   World Bank Official: Create Government Organs `Quickly' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    World Bank Official: Create Government Organs `Quickly' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB2005164194 Libreville Africa No. 1 in French 1215 GMT 20 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB2005164194 </F>
<F P=104>  Libreville Africa No. 1 </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Almost a month after the appointment of a prime 
minister, Togo is still without a government. Prime Minister 
Edem Kodjo, who has been snubbed by his opposition friends, has 
still not been able to form his government. This situation is a 
source of concern for Togo's donors, especially, the World Bank, 
which would like the new institutions to be set up quickly 
before reviving negotiations with international institutions. 
Olabire da Cruz reports from Lome: 
  [Begin da Cruz recording] After two separate meetings with 
Prime Minister Edem Kodjo and President Eyadema on 18 and 19 
May, the World Bank executive director for Togo, Mr. Jean-Pierre 
Noboude, said that he would like to see the institutions 
established quickly in order to have specific officials to talk 
to before new agreements are signed. According to Mr. Noboude, 
this should be done by the end of this month or at the beginning 
of June at the latest so that the country can benefit from some 
20 billion CFA francs to be allocated, essentially for urban 
development and the procurement of drugs by the Health Ministry. 
  For the people, Mr. Noboude's statement seems to be an 
answer 
to its SOS call to politicians to help them deal with the 
numerous problems resulting from the protracted sociopolitical 
crisis and the recent devaluation of the CFA franc. When is the 
government going to be formed? This is the question on the lips 
of Togolese, who are increasingly worried that possible aid 
might pass them by because of the institutional void which some 
people hope will be filled within the next few days or even 
hours. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

