<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Date Set for Signing Final Peace Document </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Date Set for Signing Final Peace Document </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005214694 Lisbon RDP Antena 1 Radio Network in Portuguese 
2100 GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2005214694 </F>
<F P=104>  Lisbon RDP Antena 1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A peace deal for Angola is a hair's breadth away. 
We have been informed by a diplomatic source that the Lusaka 
agreement will be signed on 6 June. One thing is certain: When 
Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos arrives in Portugal on 
27 June, there will already be peace on paper. At the moment, 
the only remaining point at the talks is that of national 
reconciliation and at stake are the provinces of Huambo and 
Benguela. These are two provinces which the National Union for 
the Total Independence of Angola [UNITA] does not want to 
relinquish. For the moment, the government does not want to 
give in to this UNITA demand. Both the government and UNITA are 
now trying to gain ground in the military field. 

</TEXT>

