<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Rwanda </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Envoy Told To Move to Nairobi; RPF Alleges `Bias' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Envoy Told To Move to Nairobi; RPF Alleges `Bias' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA2205174194 (Clandestine) Radio Muhabura in English to 
Rwanda 1130 GMT 21 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA2205174194 </F>
<F P=104>  (Clandestine) Radio Muhabura </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The UN secretary general's special representative to 
Rwanda, Dr. Jacques Roger Booh-Booh, has been told to move from 
Rwanda to Nairobi, Kenya. The instructions have been given by 
the UN secretary general, Dr. Butrus Butrus-Ghali. The Rwandan 
Patriotic Front [RPF] has been calling for the withdrawal of Dr. 
Jacques-Roger Booh-Booh from Rwanda because Dr. Booh-Booh has 
been biased against the RPF. While attempting to implement the 
Arusha peace agreement, Dr. Jacques-Roger Booh-Booh fought very 
hard to include the CDR [pro-Habyarimana's Coalition for the 
Defense of the Republic] into the broad-based transitional 
national assembly. 
  CDR is a political party of extremists which violated the 
Arusha peace agreement immediately after the agreement had been 
signed. Dr. Jacques-Roger Booh-Booh has also participated in the 
setting up of the current illegitimate government in Rwanda, a 
government of extremists which is behind the massacres that have 
been going on in Rwanda. Dr. Jacques-Roger Booh-Booh was so 
close to the extremist political group of President Habyarimana 
to the extent that Dr. Jacques-Roger Booh-Booh compromised his 
role as a mediator between the RPF and the Rwandan Government. 
  The RPF has said that it will not cooperate in any UN 
activities in Rwanda until Dr. Jacques-Roger Booh-Booh is 
withdrawn. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-48573 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr099_a_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Rwanda </F>
<H3> <TI>   RPF Against Cease-Fire, New UN Troops </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    RPF Against Cease-Fire, New UN Troops </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205175294 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 1700 
GMT 22 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2205175294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] In Rwanda the rebels of the Rwandan Patriotic 
Front [RPF] today took control first of the airport in Kigali 
and then of the Kanombe barracks, where the government army was 
holed up. [passage omitted] 
  Our correspondent Nicolas Poincare has been accompanying the 
RPF troops for several days as they advance on Kigali. He sends 
his first report this evening on the particularly tragic 
situation in Rwanda: 
  [Poincare] [passage omitted] The RPF, scenting victory, will 
not hear of a cease-fire, nor of the arrival of fresh UN troops. 
Dr Emile Roua Massirabo, deputy chairman of the RPF, explains 
that the arrival of UN troops would mean the preservation of the 
status quo, and hence continuing massacres in the areas held by 
the regular army. He said so yesterday in his headquarters in 
Kibungo: 
  [Begin Massirabo recording] When they ask for such an 
intervention force, we have the feeling that on the one hand, 
they are telling us to stop pursuing the killers, and on the 
other, they (?will not) be able to stop the massacres, and they 
will be given a free hand to continue their vile work. [end 
recording] 
  [Poincare] The UN troops can only look on impotently at this 
success. They cannot even use the airport any more. Nicolas 
Poincare, France Inter, Kibungo, Rwanda. 

</TEXT>

