<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Rwanda </F>
<H3> <TI>   RPF Official on Cease-fire, Aid Flights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    RPF Official on Cease-fire, Aid Flights </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205193994 Paris Radio France International in French 1830 
GMT 22 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2205193994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio France International </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In Rwanda a possible cease-fire has been announced 
by sources close to the United Nations. The government army 
reportedly accepted this 60-hour truce planned to start at 0600 
GMT tomorrow. The Rwandan Patriotic Front [RPF] has clearly 
stated that it does not intend to respect this cease-fire. 
Let's listen to Jacques Bihozagara, a member of the RPF 
executive committee who was appointed deputy president in the 
Arusha agreement: 
  [Begin recording] [Bihozagara] For us it is unacceptable to 
sign a cease-fire; however, if they want to surrender we are 
ready to consider the proposal. If they want a cease-fire they 
must first stop the massacre of civilians. 
  [Unidentified correspondent] What about the neutrality of 
the 
airport which the UN Mission in Rwanda [UNAMIR] has attempted to 
negotiate for several days? What will your answer be, now that 
you are in control of the airport? 
  [Bihozagara] Now that we control the airport, it is out of 
the question to negotiate its neutrality; it is rather a matter 
of asking how planes can land and take off, that's all. 
  [Correspondent] Will you differentiate between planes flying 
in humanitarian aid and those flying in UN soldiers? 
  [Bihozagara] Obviously, because we expressed our support for 
humanitarian aid and we are ready to consider the UNAMIR request 
concerning humanitarian issues. 
  [Correspondent] What about the arrival of UN reinforcements? 
  [Bihozagara] Concerning the arrival of reinforcements, I say 
that if we have accepted the principle of the UN resolution we 
have not yet discussed their deployment. We are expecting the 
United Nations to give us details concerning their mission, 
their composition and the deployment of these forces before they 
arrive. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

