<H3> <TI>   Notes Other Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Notes Other Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305090494 Paris Radio France International in French 0630 
GMT 23 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2305090494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio France International </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Jacques Bihozagara, member of the </F>
Rwandan Patriotic Front Political Bureau, by Dominique de 
Courcelles on 23 May, place not given -- recorded] 
  [Excerpts] Fierce exchanges of fire broke out early this 
morning in certain districts of Kigali, the capital of Rwanda, 
according to a Reuter report we have just received. [passage 
omitted] In theory, a cease-fire -- or rather a truce -- should 
have started in Kigali half an hour ago, at 0800 local time, at 
the initiative of the United Nations. [passage omitted] Here is 
one of the main officials of the Rwandan Patriotic Front, whom 
Dominique de Courcelles has just contacted in Geneva. He is 
Jacques Bihozagara, member of the political bureau of the 
organization: 
  [Bihozagara] I think we have to make a distinction between a 
truce and a cease-fire. We have never refused a truce for a 
specific action, for example consultations between the United 
Nations and the forces on the ground. 
  As for a cease-fire, we are saying that first you have to 
get 
a cease-fire between those who are butchering the people and the 
people themselves, but there is no question of speaking of a 
cease- fire between the fighters of the Patriotic Front and this 
routed army. 
  [De Courcelles] So after the truce we should expect the 
fighting to begin again? 
  [Bihozagara] Of course. 
  [De Courcelles] So this truce is to get an explanation of 
the 
UN mandate, because a priori you rather tend to be against a 
reinforcement of the UN troops? 
  [Bihozagara] You know, we are not formally against it, but 
we 
weren't there when the UN Security Council resolution was 
adopted in New York, so we are expecting further clarifications 
from the United Nations about its make-up, its deployment, and 
its numbers. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

