<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNITA Reacts To Aid Suspension </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UNITA Reacts To Aid Suspension </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2305085394 Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro in 
Portuguese 0600 GMT 23 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2305085394 </F>
<F P=104>  Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] In addition to its cruel, successive 
bombardments of densely populated areas, the Jose Eduardo dos 
Santos regime is once again using international relief aid as a 
weapon against the people, particularly those living in areas 
controlled by the National Union for the Total Independence of 
Angola [UNITA]. 
  Sources with the UNITA relief services today reacted to 
statements made to the Portuguese television [as heard] TSF 
[wireless] channel by the MPLA-PT [Popular Movement for the 
Liberation of Angola-Labor Party] minister for social 
reintegration. According to the minister, UNITA troops raided 
World Food Program [WFP] warehouses in the cities of Huambo, 
Uige, and Jamba. Minister Albino Malungo's remarks were 
unfortunate and have been dismissed by [name indistinct], WFP 
spokesman in Luanda. Unlike in the regime's areas, there is 
neither wholesale theft nor social evils in UNITA-administered 
territory. [passage omitted] 
  Other sources told our correspondent that Albino Malungo's 
unfounded remarks are hypocritical because he should remember 
that Norberto dos Santos, his predecessor in the same ministry, 
was dismissed for diverting relief aid donated by international 
relief agencies. The source added that such a situation is not 
applicable to UNITA-controlled areas. 
  The sources urged the international community and relief 
agencies operating in Angola not to allow themselves to be 
deceived by Jose Eduardo dos Santos' regime. The regime intends 
to use the shortages faced by Angolans to effectively implement 
its militarist plan. The sources added that the United Nations 
should as a matter of urgency review its operations in Angola so 
that these cover the whole country, without discrimination. 

</TEXT>

