<H3> <TI>   Mandela, Buthelezi Meet on Land Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mandela, Buthelezi Meet on Land Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2305091794 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0858 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2305091794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cape Town May 23 SAPA -- President Nelson Mandela 
and home affairs minister Chief Mangosuthu Buthelezi held talks 
on Monday morning on the KwaZulu land issue and the appointment 
of the KwaZulu/Natal provincial cabinet, a spokesman for the 
president's office said. 
  Press spokesman Mr Joel Netshitenzhe said at 10.30 that the 
meeting -- at Mr Mandela's official residence Westbrooke -- 
"should be over by now". The two men had talked for about 
one-and-a-half hours, he said. As far as he knew, deputy 
president Mr FW de Klerk had not been present. The intention 
was not to issue a press statement before the cabinet meeting 
due to start at 11AM. 
  Earlier, minister of land affairs Mr Derek Hanekom cancelled 
a press conference scheduled for Monday so that the president 
and cabinet could discuss the KwaZulu land issue before he was 
asked to answer any further questions on it. A spokesman for 
his office said the press conference, set up early last week, 
was to have dealt with land restitution. After the KwaZulu land 
issue hit the headlines questions on it at the press conference 
were unavoidable. "Mr Hanekom would not like to comment until 
we hear something from the president," she said. 
  Last week the ANC in KwaZulu/Natal asked to be excused from 
proceedings in the provincial cabinet after expressing 
dissatisfaction with the ministerial portfolios allocated to it. 
Provincial premier Dr Frank Mdladlose said a meeting to discuss 
the issue had been called for Tuesday. 
  It was also reported last week that the day before former 
President de Klerk was voted out of office, he ceded control 
over some three million hectares of KwaZulu state land to a 
trust headed by King Goodwill Zwelethini. ANC leaders in Natal 
were enraged by the move, calling it a "deal made behind the 
people's backs". 

</TEXT>

