<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mandela, Buthelezi Comment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mandela, Buthelezi Comment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2305101494 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0948 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2305101494 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cape Town May 23 SAPA -- President Nelson Mandela on 
Monday expressed his satisfaction following discussions on the 
KwaZulu land transfer with the minister of home affairs, Chief 
Mangosuthu Buthelezi. The two men met at Westbrooke, the 
president's official residence, for about one-and-a-half hours. 
  "I am happy with the candid and harmonious manner in which 
we 
addressed this issue. We are discussing it as a very important 
and sensitive issue. I'm sure that with the good relationship 
between ourselves, we can address the matter to the satisfaction 
of all," Mr Mandela said. 
  President Mandela said both he and Chief Buthelezi would now 
refer the matter to their respective organisations for any 
decision. "I am satisfied with the progress which we have made. 
It now depends of our organisations," he said. 
  Chief Buthelezi said he had explained to Mr Mandela that the 
land in question had been transferred to the KwaZulu government 
three years ago. The government had then decided to transfer 
the land to different Zulu tribes living in the area as communal 
land. "There is nothing new in this. There is no hanky panky. 
It is insulting to suggest that the land was given to the 
king." He accused the media of "trying to drive a wedge between 
the ANC and the IFP [Inkatha Freedom Party]". 
  The two leaders also discussed the allocation of cabinet 
portfolios to the IFP and the siting of the KwaZulu/Natal 
provincial capital. Chief Buthelezi said the location of the 
capital should be put to the people of the province in a 
referendum. 
  He said the IFP accepted the fact that it would not get the 
health portfolio as initially indicated. The ANC's Dr Nkosazana 
Zuma has been appointed minister of health. 
  The chief, who was accompanied by deputy minister of 
security 
services Joe Matthews and Prince Gideon Zulu of the Zulu royal 
house, responded angrily when a journalist asked whether the 
land transfer may be repealed. "It seems to me you don't want 
peace in South Africa," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

