<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Buthelezi Dismisses Allegations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Buthelezi Dismisses Allegations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2305104194 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1025 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2305104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cape Town May 23 SAPA -- Suggestions that the 
KwaZulu land deal was intended to lure the Inkatha Freedom Party 
into the April elections were "rubbish" and "nonsense", home 
affairs minister Chief Mangosuthu Buthelezi asserted on Monday. 
"It was the legislation passed in Parliament that brought me 
into the election," Chief Buthelezi said. 
  Answering reporters' questions on his way to joining his 
cabinet colleagues for their first meeting at Tuynhuys, Mr 
Buthelezi said the Ingonyama [kings'] Trust Act had been debated 
in open session in the KwaZulu Legislative Assembly. In terms of 
the legislation, the 1.2 million hectares of KwaZulu tribal land 
-- that would have become state property under the new 
constitution -- was ceded to Zulu King Goodwill Zwelithini. The 
legislation had been approved by former President FW de Klerk 
"in the way that he signs all legislation". 
  Mr de Klerk approved the Ingonyama Trust Act on April 25, 
four days after it was passed by the KwaZulu government. "All 
communal land was always protected. It was to prevent it 
becoming state land," he said. 
  The land was transferred to the KwaZulu government three 
years ago. "I don't find anything controversial in it," he 
said. Chief Buthelezi said the issue would not be discussed at 
the cabinet meeting. 

</TEXT>

